        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down</placeName>
                    <date>Sept 5</date>
                    <salute>My dear Harry</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am very much obliged for the Columbine seed &amp; for your note which made us laugh heartily.—</p>
<p>I had no idea what trouble the counting must have been, I had not the least conception that there would have been so many pods. I am very much interested on this point, &amp; therefore to make assurance sure, I repeat your figures, viz 560 &amp; 742 pods on two plants &amp; <hi rend="doubleUnderline">7200</hi> on another. Does the latter number really mean pods &amp; not seeds? Upon my life I am sorry to give so much trouble, but I sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> be <hi rend="doubleUnderline">so much</hi> obliged for a few <hi rend="underline">average</hi> size pods, put up separately that I may count the seeds in each pod; for though I counted the seeds in the pods sent before, I hardly dare trust them without counting more. Moreover I sadly want more seed itself for one of my experiments.—</p>
<p>The young cabbages are coming up already.</p>
<p>Thank you much about the asparagus seed; as it is so rare a plant, you are my only chance.—</p>
<p>We have been grieved to hear about poor Anne &amp; Tom.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>Your affect<hi rend="superscript">te</hi>. screw | C. Darwin</p>
<p>Have you become acquainted with M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Huxley; I think you would find him a pleasant acquaintance. He is a very clever man.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
                <div type="tnotes">
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n1">2.6 put up separately] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi></note>
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n2">2.7 pod;] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi></note>
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n3">2.8 itself] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi></note>
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n4">5.1 grieved] ‘ri’ <hi rend="italic">over illeg</hi></note>
                </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5017.xml">Henry Allen Wedgwood</ref> was CD’s cousin and brother-in-law.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Dated on the basis of the subject of the letter. CD was investigating the comparative fertility of wild and cultivated plants. See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-1748.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to J. S. Henslow, 23 [August or September 1855]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5043.xml">Thomas Josiah Wedgwood</ref> and his wife <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4999.xml">Anne Maria</ref>. Tom was a brother of Harry’s wife <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5023.xml">Jessie</ref>.</note>
